Why is Accuracy Alone Not Enough?

Accuracy tells us the percentage of correct predictions, but it does not tell us what kind of mistakes the model is making.

A model can have high accuracy and still be useless in important real-world situations.

1. Fraud Detection

Suppose a bank has:

1000 transactions
990 Genuine
10 Fraud

If a model predicts:

Every transaction = Genuine

Accuracy:

1000
990
	​

=99%

The accuracy is 99%, which looks excellent.

But the model failed to detect all 10 fraud transactions.

For a bank, this model is not useful despite its high accuracy.

2. Medical Diagnosis

Imagine a disease screening test:

100 patients
95 Healthy
5 Sick

If the model predicts:

Everyone = Healthy

Accuracy:

95%

However, all 5 sick patients are missed.

In healthcare, missing a sick patient (False Negative) can be very serious, so accuracy alone is not enough.

3. Imbalanced Datasets

Many real-world datasets are imbalanced.

Example:

99% Normal Cases
1% Important Cases

Examples:

Fraud Detection
Cancer Detection
Network Intrusion Detection

A model can achieve very high accuracy simply by predicting the majority class every time.

Therefore accuracy can be misleading.

4. Different Error Types Matter

A confusion matrix shows:

True Positive (TP)
True Negative (TN)
False Positive (FP)
False Negative (FN)

Different mistakes have different costs.

Fraud Detection
False Negative = Fraud not detected

Very costly.

Medical Diagnosis
False Negative = Sick patient predicted healthy

Potentially dangerous.

Email Spam Filter
False Positive = Important email marked as spam

Can cause users to miss important messages.

Interview Answer

Accuracy alone is not enough because it only tells us how many predictions are correct. In problems such as fraud detection, medical diagnosis, and other imbalanced datasets, a model can achieve high accuracy while still making critical mistakes. Metrics such as precision, recall, F1-score, and the confusion matrix help us understand the types of errors and evaluate the model more effectively -->